    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about muscle growth and saw two different terms: mechanical tension and metabolic stress. can u explain the difference between them and which one is more important for hypertrophy?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Mechanical tension is the muscular tension created when you lift heavy weights, causing microscopic damage to the muscle fibers. Metabolic stress refers to the buildup of metabolites like lactate during high-volume, shorter-rest training. Both are crucial for hypertrophy, but many experts suggest that maximizing mechanical tension is the most potent driver for significant muscle growth. Think of it this way: heavy lifting (tension) is the primary stimulus, while the \"pump\" (metabolic stress) is a powerful secondary contributor.",
      "source": "target",
