    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if tension is the main driver, how does that actually work on a cellular level? like what exactly is happening to the muscle fibers when that tension is applied?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When mechanical tension is applied, the force stretches the muscle fibers and its surrounding connective tissues, which activates various cellular signaling pathways. This mechanical stress signals the muscle cell to initiate repair and adaptation processes. Essentially, the micro-trauma from the high tension triggers satellite cells to fuse with existing muscle fibers, leading to an increase in muscle protein synthesis and actual growth. This process is how the muscle becomes stronger and larger over time.",
      "source": "target",
