    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u go deeper into that part about the satellite cells and the repair process? i'm curious about how the body actually \"senses\" the stress and starts the rebuilding part.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The muscle cells detect the intense mechanical stress through mechanosensors embedded in the sarcolemma, which are like tiny stress gauges. When these receptors are activated by the heavy load, they send chemical signals into the cell's nucleus. This signaling cascade then stimulates the activation and proliferation of satellite cells, which are dormant muscle stem cells. These active satellite cells then donate their nuclei to the damaged myofibers, allowing them to synthesize more proteins and increase the muscle's size.",
      "source": "target",
